STEPS ON FLEX WINDOWS:-
✅ 🔧 1. Install required tools
You need:
•	Flex 
•	GCC (comes with MinGW or similar) 
•	Easiest setup:
Install MinGW or a bundle like “WinFlexBison”.
________________________________________
✅ 📁 2. Create your Flex file
1.	Open Notepad 
2.	Paste your code 
3.	Save as: 
spccexp4.l
⚠️ Important:
•	Save type → All Files (.) 
•	NOT .txt 
________________________________________
✅ 💻 3. Open Command Prompt
Press:
Win + R → type cmd → Enter
________________________________________
✅ 📂 4. Go to your file location
Example:
cd Desktop
(or wherever you saved spccexp4.l)
________________________________________
✅ ⚙️ 5. Run Flex
flex spccexp4.l
👉 This creates:
lex.yy.c
________________________________________
✅ 🛠️ 6. Compile using GCC
gcc lex.yy.c -o spccexp4.exe
👉 This creates:
spccexp4.exe
________________________________________
✅ ▶️ 7. Run the program
spccexp4.exe (or spccexp4)
IF YOU WANT TO RUN AGAIN DIRECTLY WRITE ONLY THE FILENAME IN CMD INSIDE THE SAVED FOLDER (MAKE SURE .exe FILE EXIST FROM ABOVE STEPS)




Lexical Analyzer using Finite Automata:-
%option noyywrap
%{
#include<stdio.h>
%}

%%
"int"|"float"|"char"|"if"|"else"|"while"|"return"   { printf("Keyword: %s\n", yytext); }

[0-9]+      { printf("Number: %s\n", yytext); }

[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z0-9_]*   { printf("Identifier: %s\n", yytext); }

[+\-*/=]   { printf("Operator: %s\n", yytext); }

[;(){}]    { printf("Special Symbol: %s\n", yytext); }

[ \t\n]    ;

.          { printf("Invalid: %s\n", yytext); }
%%

int main()
{
    printf("Enter the code:\n");
    yylex();
    return 0;
}





